<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
  A FUI <code>&lt;we-filter-chip&gt;</code> is a <strong>transient</strong> custom element (family A of the
  block-standard runtime-shape rule): on upgrade it <strong>replaces itself with a native
  <code>&lt;button class="fui-filter-chip"&gt;</code></strong> via <code>replaceWith()</code>, so the
  original node — and any listener bound <em>directly</em> to it — is detached and discarded. WE-side JS that
  wired those chips loses the handler, and any cached element reference goes stale. This shipped <em>twice</em>
  as a regression on the <code>/backlog/</code> Prioritisation table: the summary count pills
  (<code>data-pfilter</code>) used a direct <code>addEventListener</code> and silently stopped filtering the
  moment the FUI module upgraded them. The decision (<strong>#1960</strong>): where does the durable fix live,
  and how is it enforced?
</p>

<h2>Finding 1 — only the host element's <em>own</em> listeners are lost</h2>
<p>
  The self-replacement (<code>fui:blocks/transient/TransientElement.ts</code>) <strong>moves</strong> child
  nodes rather than cloning them, so listeners on <em>children</em> survive; and it <strong>copies every
  attribute</strong> onto the native button, so <code>data-*</code> and a computed <code>aria-pressed</code>
  <strong>survive the upgrade</strong>. What is lost is only the listeners bound to the transient host node
  itself — and the DOM exposes <strong>no API to enumerate or transfer an element's own listeners</strong>, so
  a "preserve the bound handlers" fix is <em>mechanically impossible</em>. This is distinct from a
  <strong>standard custom-element upgrade</strong>, which keeps the <em>same</em> node and therefore keeps its
  listeners — the footgun is specific to the explicit self-<em>replace</em> variant, not to progressive
  enhancement in general.
</p>

<h2>Finding 2 — FUI already has a stable-event precedent, but only on <em>persistent</em> hosts</h2>
<p>
  A constellation-wide survey of FUI interactive elements splits cleanly: every <strong>persistent</strong>
  (B-family) element — tabs, stepper, dockable — dispatches a bubbling CustomEvent on its stable host
  (<code>tab-change</code>, <code>step-change</code>, <code>dock</code>; the convention is
  <code>new CustomEvent(name, { detail, bubbles: true, cancelable })</code>). But <strong>every transient</strong>
  (A-family) element — button, badge, meter, text-field, filter-chip — exposes state via <strong>native events
  and attributes</strong>, never a CustomEvent. So a stable bubbling change-event is a real FUI pattern, but
  it has <em>no precedent on a transient element</em>.
</p>

<h2>Finding 3 — an open <code>addEventListener</code> sniff is an already-rejected gate shape</h2>
<p>
  One way to enforce a "delegate, don't bind directly" rule is a lint flagging <code>addEventListener</code> on
  a chip selector. The platform has <strong>already ruled on exactly this</strong>: the
  <code>compose-dont-handroll</code> rule (#933) declares open-ended <code>addEventListener</code> sniffing a
  <strong>"false-positive factory"</strong> and mandates a <strong>curated, selector-scoped deny-list</strong>
  (warn-first → ERROR) instead — with a working precedent in <code>COMPOSE_DENY_LIST</code>. So a gate here is
  feasible only as a curated list keyed to the <em>known</em> chip selectors; it cannot generalise to "a
  listener bound to any self-replacing element" without becoming the rejected open sniff.
</p>

<h2>Finding 4 (decisive) — "which side owns the fix" is a false dichotomy</h2>
<p>
  The original framing — <em>does WE carry a consumer rule (Fork A) or does FUI guarantee a stable surface
  (Fork B)</em> — collapses under the standing test. <strong>WE codifies a consumer rule either way</strong>
  (WE holds zero implementation, so even under Fork B it "only consumes and codifies the consumer-facing
  contract"), and a FUI event would be <strong>additive, not exclusive</strong> — native <code>click</code>
  still bubbles to the same delegated ancestor, so an event <em>supplements</em> delegation rather than
  replacing it. The decision therefore decomposes into:
</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>A forced invariant (codify, not a fork):</strong> the WE consumer contract — delegate on a stable
    ancestor, never cache the transient node, read <code>data-*</code>/<code>aria-pressed</code> (which survive
    the upgrade). The only alternative (bind directly to the chip) <em>is</em> the shipped regression. This fix
    already shipped in <code>backlog-table-sort.js</code> and is netted by a deterministic mock-chip Playwright
    lane.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 1 — enforcement:</strong> default <em>interaction-test lane only</em> (no source gate), since
    #933 bans the open sniff and the lane catches the real regression; the alternative is a #933-shaped curated
    deny-list.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Fork 2 — should FUI additionally ship a stable <code>chip-change</code> event?</strong> default
    <em>no, not now</em>: delegation works today, a <code>chip-change</code> event <strong>double-fires with
    native <code>click</code></strong>, and it adds a permanent API to a control whose transient family was
    chosen to lean on native events kept. Un-gate trigger: a consumer that genuinely cannot delegate (e.g. a
    framework/non-DOM binding).
  </li>
</ul>
<p>
  Citation-scope correction surfaced by the skeptic pass: the transient-mechanism ruling (#1381) governs
  <em>mechanism-selection</em> (transient vs persistent vs shadow), <strong>not</strong> event-API design — its
  "native events are kept" clause argues <em>for</em> delegating on native <code>click</code>, the opposite of
  what an early draft cited it for.
</p>
